\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.18}{\ignorespaces Electric field in y-direction $E^\pm _\mathrm {y}$ at $x=0, y=b/4, z=\pm l/2$, and the closely related power at one of the output ports in (a). The output power produced by the loop antenna is compared with that generated by the equivalent dipole moments in (b).}}{61}{figure.caption.46}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.19}{\ignorespaces Comparison of the output power produced by the loop antenna and the equivalent dipole moments, for a rotation of the loop antenna around the $y$-axis by $0$ and $\pi $.}}{62}{figure.caption.47}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.20}{\ignorespaces Electric and magnetic energy stored in the TEM cell as a function of frequency, produced by the loop antenna.}}{63}{figure.caption.48}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.21}{\ignorespaces Equivalent dipole moments in (a) and output power in (b) for two loop antenna configurations: $h=2.16\,\mathrm {mm},\, w=1.4\,\mathrm {mm}$ and $h=1.2\,\mathrm {mm},\, w=2.36\,\mathrm {mm}$. The electric dipole moment $\mathbf {m}_e$ is weighted by $\eta _0$ to enable direct comparison with $\mathbf {m}_m$.}}{63}{figure.caption.49}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.22}{\ignorespaces The voltage at the feedpoint, and the current in close proximity to the feedpoint and return path in (a). The and impedance characteristics of the loop antenna in (b).}}{64}{figure.caption.50}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.23}{\ignorespaces Surface current density on the septum induced by the loop antenna. (a) Centrally placed loop antenna without rotation at 3\,GHz, where only the TEM mode propagates. (b) The same antenna with a lateral offset of $x = 7\,\mathrm {mm}$ and a rotation angle of $\pi /4$ at 100\,MHz, a frequency at which only the TEM mode propagates. (c) The same configuration as in (b) at 3.3\,GHz, above the cut-off frequency of the TE\textsubscript {01} mode, which is therefore also excited.}}{67}{figure.caption.51}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.24}{\ignorespaces Frequency-dependent output power transmitted by the offset and rotated loop antenna ($x=7\,\mathrm {mm}$, $\pi /4$) to one output port. The contributions of the TEM and TE\textsubscript {01} modes are shown separately, highlighting the resonance near $3.21\,\mathrm {GHz}$ and the dominant coupling via the TE\textsubscript {01} mode.}}{68}{figure.caption.52}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.25}{\ignorespaces (a) shows the full equivalent circuit of the small loop antenna, accounting for several physical effects not needed for the purposes of this investigation. The reduced equivalent circuit in (b) is sufficient.}}{68}{figure.caption.53}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.26}{\ignorespaces Model of the loop antenna connected to a feedpoint mounted on a PEC surface with a side length of $\lambda /2$, where $\lambda $ corresponds to the free-space wavelength of the solution frequency. This configuration enables the investigation of the loop antenna reactance without influence of the TEM cell.}}{69}{figure.caption.54}%
